<h2>How to Measure Body Composition</h2>
    <h3>DEXA scan (most accurate)</h3>
    <p>Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry provides the most accurate body composition measurement available, distinguishing fat, lean mass, and bone density by body region. Available at specialist clinics and some gyms. Cost: $50–150 per scan. Useful for tracking changes over 3–6 month periods.</p>
    <h3>Hydrostatic weighing</h3>
    <p>Underwater weighing — considered a gold standard alongside DEXA. Less widely available but highly accurate. Uses the principle that fat is less dense than water.</p>
    <h3>Skinfold calipers</h3>
    <p>A trained assessor measures skin fold thickness at 3–7 body sites and calculates body fat percentage. Accurate within ±3–4% when done correctly. Inexpensive and widely available at gyms and fitness centres.</p>
    <h3>Bioelectrical impedance (smart scales)</h3>
    <p>Consumer smart scales estimate body fat via electrical resistance. Convenient and cheap but can vary ±5–8% based on hydration, time of day, and recent meals. Useful for tracking trends rather than absolute values.</p>
    <h3>Waist circumference (practical proxy)</h3>
    <p>Not a direct body composition measure, but waist circumference above 80cm (women) or 94cm (men) reliably indicates excess visceral fat — the most metabolically dangerous type.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>How to Improve Body Composition</h2>
    <p>Improving body composition means reducing fat mass and increasing (or maintaining) muscle mass. The three key levers are:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Calorie deficit:</strong> Creates fat loss. Aim for 400–500 kcal below TDEE. Use our <a href="/calorie-deficit-calculator" style="color:var(--accent);">Deficit Calculator</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>High protein intake:</strong> 1.6–2.2g/kg bodyweight preserves muscle during a deficit.</li>
      <li><strong>Resistance training:</strong> 2–3 sessions per week stimulates muscle protein synthesis, preventing muscle loss and potentially building muscle simultaneously with fat loss (body recomposition).</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="warn-callout"><p>⚠️ The scale is an incomplete picture of body composition progress. Someone starting resistance training may lose 2kg of fat, gain 1kg of muscle, and see only a 1kg change on the scale — while dramatically improving their body composition and metabolic health.</p></div>
  </div>


  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>How to Measure Body Composition at Home</h2>
    <p>Without clinical equipment, several practical methods can track body composition changes over time. None are perfectly accurate, but used consistently, they show meaningful trends:</p>
    <div class="card" style="padding:0;overflow:hidden;margin:16px 0;">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Accuracy</th><th>Cost</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Waist circumference</strong></td><td>Good proxy for visceral fat</td><td>Free (tape measure)</td><td>Weekly tracking</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Waist-to-height ratio</strong></td><td>Strong metabolic risk predictor</td><td>Free</td><td>Metabolic risk assessment</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Skinfold callipers</strong></td><td>±3–5% with practice</td><td>£10–30</td><td>Budget body fat tracking</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Bioelectrical impedance (BIA scale)</strong></td><td>±3–8%, variable</td><td>£30–200</td><td>Trend tracking (not single readings)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Progress photos</strong></td><td>Visual, not numerical</td><td>Free</td><td>Motivation, visual change</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>DEXA scan</strong></td><td>±1–2% (clinical gold standard)</td><td>£50–150 per scan</td><td>Baseline + annual check</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>For most people, combining <strong>waist circumference + body weight + progress photos</strong> provides a complete enough picture without the cost or variability of body fat scales. Use our <a href="/waist-to-height-ratio">Waist-to-Height Ratio Calculator</a> and <a href="/body-fat">Body Fat Estimator</a> for a more complete view.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>Healthy Body Composition Ranges by Sex and Age</h2>
    <p>The following body fat percentage ranges are based on Gallagher et al. (2000) and are widely used in clinical and fitness settings:</p>
    <div class="card" style="padding:0;overflow:hidden;margin:16px 0;">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>Women (20–39)</th><th>Women (40–59)</th><th>Women (60+)</th><th>Men (20–39)</th><th>Men (40–59)</th><th>Men (60+)</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Essential fat</td><td>10–13%</td><td>10–13%</td><td>10–13%</td><td>2–5%</td><td>2–5%</td><td>2–5%</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Healthy</strong></td><td><strong>21–32%</strong></td><td><strong>23–33%</strong></td><td><strong>24–35%</strong></td><td><strong>8–19%</strong></td><td><strong>11–21%</strong></td><td><strong>13–24%</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Overweight</td><td>33–38%</td><td>34–39%</td><td>36–41%</td><td>20–24%</td><td>22–27%</td><td>25–29%</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td>Obese</td><td>≥39%</td><td>≥40%</td><td>≥42%</td><td>≥25%</td><td>≥28%</td><td>≥30%</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>Note that healthy body fat percentage increases with age — this reflects normal physiological changes in fat distribution and muscle mass, not a lowering of health standards. For a personalised body fat estimate, use our <a href="/body-fat">Body Fat Calculator</a>.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-section">
  <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is body composition and why does it matter?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Body composition refers to the proportions of fat mass versus lean mass (muscle, bone, organs, water) in your body. It matters because two people at the same weight can have radically different health risks and physical appearances depending on how much of their weight is fat versus muscle. Scale weight alone does not capture this distinction.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I improve my body composition without losing weight?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Body recomposition — gaining muscle while losing fat simultaneously — is possible and produces dramatic appearance changes with minimal scale movement. It requires adequate protein (2.0–2.4g/kg/day), progressive resistance training, a modest calorie deficit or maintenance intake, and sufficient sleep. It is most achievable in beginners and those returning from a training break.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is a healthy body fat percentage?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">For men, 10–20% body fat is healthy (athletic: 6–13%). For women, 18–28% is healthy (athletic: 14–20%). Body fat naturally increases slightly with age. Below the essential fat level (3–5% for men, 10–13% for women) carries serious health risks. Above the obese threshold (25%+ for men, 32%+ for women) is associated with elevated metabolic disease risk.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is body fat percentage or BMI more useful for tracking progress?</button>
    <div class="faq-a">Body fat percentage provides more specific and actionable information for people who exercise, as it shows whether changes are from fat or muscle. BMI is simpler to calculate and useful for initial screening. Using both together — plus waist circumference — gives the most complete picture. Progress photos and clothing fit are also valuable, free tools.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I have good body composition but high BMI?</button>
